english:
  title: Letter Presented to Zhao Langjun Chong
  author: Lee Gyou-bo
  language: eng
  text: "On this day, I have heard it said that a woman of abundant flesh and graceful bearing, whose every smile blooms into a thousand expressions of charm, is accounted the most beautiful under heaven. Yet such a beauty, though a thousand matchmakers should petition for her hand and a thousand nobles should seek her favor, will scarce deign to accept them—not out of fear, but because she trusts in the sufficiency of her own allure.\n\nConversely, a woman with protruding brow and harelip, bent and crooked in frame, is accounted the ugliest under heaven. She marries only into the households of common merchants and low peddlers. Yet should a man of vigor and worth by misfortune take her as his own, she becomes so overjoyed that she might burst. She paints her face anew, adorns herself with pins and ornaments, and boasts of her fortune to all she meets. When her husband hears of this, shame overwhelms him. Upon seeing her again, he furrows his brow, spits upon the ground, and refuses even to glance her way. Yet the woman, ignorant of her own ugliness, weeps day and night until her cries echo through the neighboring lanes, drawing crowds to console her. Her husband, fearing her tears will not cease, begins to treat her with greater kindness, bestowing upon her fine silks and precious metals, even building her a house of her own. \n\nWhen the courtesans of the realm, those of beauty and renown, learn of this, they reason among themselves: \"If this man cannot bear to abandon an ugly woman, how much less would he abandon one such as ourselves?\" And so they come adorned in silks and fragrant with perfume, each racing ahead of the last, each fearing to arrive too late. Within years, all the celebrated beauties converge upon his household.\n\nNow, my own mediocrity and roughness are not merely the protruding brow and harelip of ugliness—they fall far short even of that. And your lordship's commanding presence and illustrious station are not merely the vigor and beauty of such a man—they far exceed it.\n\nIn those earlier days, your lordship did not regard me as worthless. From my youth, you received me with great warmth and intimacy, even pledging our brotherhood and offering me your whole heart. I, being rash and unworthy, presumed to cultivate my speech and manner, to flatter and please you, all the while believing our bond was fixed and firm. I spoke freely and boasted to all around: \"Among all the scholars known to your lordship, none is known as I am.\" With such confidence, my every step seemed guided by your hand.\n\nYet now I must ask: do you regard me with shame, and like that man, will you turn away and spit? Or do you fear my ceaseless weeping and choose, after all, to remain my friend? Should you choose indifference, my tears and laments will grow louder by the day, and your reputation as a friend to worthy men will surely diminish. \n\nBut if you cannot bring yourself to abandon an old companion—if you would but veil my flaws and, recalling that the wise beauty Wuyan was once despised, lend me but one word of patronage to open for me the path to office, allowing me to ascend from the Golden Gate to the Jade Hall, to receive the honors and provisions due an official—then what is that man's provision of house and silk to an ugly wife compared to this?\n\nShould you do so, all the scholars under heaven will marvel at your virtue and say: \"How noble is your lordship, who would not abandon even one so worthless as this, and whose patronage is so generous! How much less would he abandon men of true merit?\" And then those of embroidered heart and woven virtue will flock to your service like stars racing through the heavens, each fearing to arrive too late. Will not Yan Hui, Min Ziqian, Zengzi, and Shi Yu all emerge from your household? Your name as a man who receives others with humility and lifts up scholars will be recorded in the annals of history and shine imperishably through ten thousand ages.\n\nI humbly pray that your lordship will present my words to Minister Yue, and surely he will ask: \"What manner of man is this?\" Should he smile and nod his approval, it would be my great fortune. Yet all depends upon your lordship's judgment.\n\nTrusting in our old bond, I have presumed to trouble you with these many words. I dare not say more. I tremble with reverent fear."
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Wuyan (無鹽) and Zhongli Chun (鍾離春) were references to a famously ugly woman of antiquity whose wisdom and virtue made her invaluable to her ruler, symbolizing how inner worth can transcend outward appearance.
  - key: ''
    value: The four sages mentioned—Yan Hui (顔淵), Min Ziqian (閔子騫), Zengzi (曾參), and Shi Yu (史魚)—were celebrated disciples of Confucius known for their virtue and moral integrity, representing the ideal scholars one would wish to attract.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Golden Gate' (金門) and 'Jade Hall' (玉堂) are metaphorical references to high imperial office and the honors that attend such position.
